              <h3 class="title"><a href="#"><span>Nova Scotia Youth Corps program that employs young people in the environmental field gets five more years of funding</span></a></h3>
              <div class="content" style="display: none;"><p><strong>Clean Foundation has signed a new five-year agreement with the Nova Scotia Department of Environment to continue delivering the innovative Nova Scotia Youth Conservation Corps program. The Province has also increased their funding to $100,000 per year.</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Managed by Clean Foundation, a non-profit environmental organization based in Nova Scotia, the Youth Corps provides youth aged 15-30 with training and employment opportunities in the environmental field. It also helps build the capacity of communities in Nova Scotia while improving their local environment. The Youth Corps, a program started in 1989 by the Nova Scotia Environment dept., has since helped thousands of youth better the environment and gain the career skills they need to successfully enter the green economy.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>In 2015, 58 students worked on projects with non-profit organizations, community groups, municipalities and First Nation’s groups throughout the province. The Youth Corps has both a 9-week summer employment program, and a 15-week leadership program that focuses on under- and unemployment youth, most notably in rural and First Nations communities. Clean is now accepting applications for summer placements and will continue to do so until the end of May.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Examples of the types of projects the students work on include:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li>Active transportation and trail development</li>
<li>Stream restoration and water quality testing</li>
<li>Pollinator, food, and rain garden installation</li>
<li>Wildlife rehabilitation and conservation</li>
<li>Environmentally focused children’s day camps</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>In Nova Scotia, more than half of our young people leave the province after graduation. And it can be difficult to get local jobs without experience. Clean believes that offering youth environmental skills and awareness is crucial to the economic and environmental sustainability of our province.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Here are video profiles of two Youth Corps participants who were in the 15-week leadership program: </em></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-13547" src="http://clean.ns.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/shannahpfeature-150x150.jpg" alt="shannahpfeature" width="150" height="150" />Shanna Francis:</strong> A participant in the Youth Corps’ Leadership Program talks about her work at the Mi’kmaq Environmental Learning Centre in Eskasoni – and how education can help preserve Mi’kmaq traditions and promote sustainable resource use. <a href="https://youtu.be/vKbhiscnozI">Watch now &gt;</a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-13415" src="http://clean.ns.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/charliemarshall-150x150.jpg" alt="charliemarshall" width="150" height="150" />Charlie Marshall:</strong> A participant in the Youth Corps’ Leadership Program talks about his work at the Mi’kmaw Conservation Group, and what the leadership program meant to him. <a href="https://youtu.be/Zsn1e19EGK4">Watch now &gt;</a></p>
</div>
