                                                    <div class="content-block">
              <h3 class="title"><a href="#"><span>Clean Foundation to attend Global Climate Conference in Paris</span></a></h3>
              <div class="content" style="display: none;"><p><strong>The next Global Climate Conference (also known as COP21) will be held in Paris from November 30th to December 11th. Canada and almost 200 other countries, as well as thousands of organizations, will work to adopt a universal agreement to limit global emissions production and help societies transition to low-carbon economies.</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There is consensus among most governments and scientists that to keep the climate system in balance requires us to limit warming below an average of 2°C above pre-industrial levels by century’s end. Each country must submit Intended Nationally Determined Contributions (INDCs) to reduce greenhouse gas emissions before <a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/youth-engagement/talking-climate-change-with-kids/global-climate-conference-in-paris/">COP21</a> and a summary of these contributions has been created to represent the cumulative impact of these national efforts and to determine if they are enough to limit warming.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Without the Paris commitments, with business as usual, we are on track to see 4-6 °C warming by the end of the century. This would mean significant changes to the Earth as we know it. If all the commitments in the INDC’s are carried out, the Earth will likely experience a warming of 2.7°C by 2100. We are close, but more aggressive commitments and accelerated ambition are needed to keep our planet below 2°C.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Since the early days of international climate change summits, non-governmental organizations (NGOs) have been actively involved, attending sessions and exchanging views with other participants, including delegates. It is recognized that this involvement allows vital experience, expertise, information and perspectives from civil society to be brought into the process to generate new insights and approaches.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Furthermore, the access and participation of observers to the process promotes transparency in this increasingly complex universal problem. Such participation flourishes in an atmosphere of mutual trust which acknowledges respect for others and their opinions, and takes into account the nature of intergovernmental sessions.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Clean Foundation will be attending the Climate Conference to learn from other delegates, and to share our experience, particularly in the following areas:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/youth-engagement/">Youth engagement</a> in air quality, climate change, renewables, and energy efficiency (we have  over 20 years&#8217; experience in the schools, engaging thousands of children each year).</li>
<li>Supporting <a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/youth-engagement/talking-climate-change-with-kids/">elementary school engagement</a> with COP21 across Canada.</li>
<li>Collaborative, multi-sectoral approaches to climate change adaptation, as is being piloted with our <a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/water/atlantic-stormwater/">Atlantic Stormwater Initiative</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/youth-engagement/nova-scotia-youth-conservation-corps-2/">Youth training, internships and mentoring</a> for success in a green economy.</li>
<li>Energy efficiency program design and implementation to address <a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/energy/homewarming-low-income-homeowner-energy-upgrades/">energy poverty</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/waste/ship-to-shore/">Fisher engagement</a> in ocean literacy and stewardship.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>We are also interested in learning about other methods of supporting local and national targets, including climate finance, climate policy, adaptation strategies, municipal leadership and micro-financing.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Clean will be posting updates from the Climate Change Conference on Facebook and Twitter.</em></p>
</div>
            </div>
                                                    <div class="content-block">
              <h3 class="title"><a href="#"><span>Talking about climate change with kids - Clean offers resources for teachers</span></a></h3>
              <div class="content" style="display: none;"><p><strong>Clean wants to help educators teach about climate change &amp; the upcoming Global Climate Conference</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>We all know how important it is to tackle climate change. It’s affecting animals, wild spaces, communities and even the economy. That’s why the upcoming Global Climate Conference is a critical opportunity for the world to come together to chart a new path.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>We believe it’s vital to involve as many young people as we can. We know they care about the Earth and their communities. We also know that given the chance, they have strong opinions and clear ideas about how to fix the problems.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There will be a very important Global Climate Conference in Paris from November 30th to December 11th. Canada and almost 200 other countries, as well as thousands of organizations, will work to adopt a universal agreement to limit global emissions production and help societies transition to low-carbon economies. It will be one of the biggest international summits ever.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Clean Foundation is providing <a href="http://clean.ns.ca/programs/youth-engagement/talking-climate-change-with-kids/">climate change resources to equip elementary-level educators</a> with information and activities that can be easily integrated into their daily lessons. We hope this will help teachers involve students and promote discussion about the important negotiations in Paris that will have a direct impact on their futures.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
            </div>
                                                    <div class="content-block">
              <h3 class="title"><a href="#"><span>Clean Foundation welcomes new Federal Environment Minister and looks forward to green action</span></a></h3>
              <div class="content" style="display: none;"><p>Clean Foundation welcomes Ms. Catherine McKenna as the new Minister of Environment and Climate Change.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>“All new governments bring renewed energy and ideas, and Clean looks forward to federal action on the environment and the realities of climate change,” says Chris Morrissey, Executive Director of Clean Foundation.</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>And as an organization based in the Atlantic, Clean also welcomes Mr. Hunter Tootoo as the new Minister of Fisheries of Oceans.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Clean encourages all level of governments in Canada to work for sustainable development. “A healthy environment is the foundation of a healthy economy and society, no matter where you live, what your cultural background is, or where you sit on the political spectrum,” adds Morrissey.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>By adding Climate Change to the name of the environment department, the new government has signaled the importance of climate issues in Canada. Reducing carbon pollution is critical for our environment, and also offers economic opportunities in areas such as clean energy.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Federal Government has said it will work with provincial governments on climate change, and Clean encourages the government to also involve the many non-profit organizations across Canada that are working hard to improve our environment.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Clean is also pleased to see a Federal Cabinet that is reflective of the diversity of Canada, and joins Mi’kmaq civil society groups in welcoming the increased presence of Indigenous Peoples at the highest levels of government power in Canada.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
